===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|bal|lang=enm}}, {{term|ball|lang=enm}}, {{term|balle|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|*beall}}, {{m|ang|*bealla||round object, ball}} or {{etyl|non|en}} {{term|bǫllr||a ball|lang=non}} (whence the Icelandic {{term|böllur||scrotum; penis; a ball|lang=is}}), both from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*balluz}}, {{m|gem-pro|*ballô||ball}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*bʰoln-||bubble}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*bʰel-||to blow, inflate, swell}}. Cognate with {{etyl|osx|-}} {{term|ball|lang=osx}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|bal|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|goh|-}} {{term|bal|lang=goh}}, {{term|ballo|lang=goh}} ({{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Ball||ball|lang=de}}; {{term|Ballen||bale|lang=de}}). Related forms in Romance are borrowings from Germanic. See also {{l/en|balloon}}, {{l/en|bale}}.

